* Type 2 diabetes and me – online course
When I was diagnosed with type 1 diabetes at age 14, I felt my life was going
to go downhill and I wouldn’t be able to achieve anything in my life. Plenty
of people living with diabetes use their condition as an excuse: I'm not one
I remember being in a hospital bed one evening crying because I felt this was
the end and I wouldn’t be able to do what my friends could do and people would
look at me funny. Shortly after someone else with diabetes came and spoke to
me in the ward about their experiences. It was around then that I learned
various athletes also had type 1 diabetes and this made me think maybe it
I am now a professional body builder with a low calorie and carbohydrate diet
– I work out for more than two hours a day and recently won the Mr Australia
Younger generations are often concerned with body image but living with
diabetes gives the best possible advantage to look great and be healthy when
compared to the wider community – because we are forced to be more aware of
Life with diabetes has become easier because I changed my mindset, my habits
and my lifestyle. I have maintained a positive attitude towards diabetes to
enable me to push my boundaries. My staple diet consists of Barramundi, green
beans and salmon and I help other people living with diabetes to achieve their
weight loss goals and their dreams – one of the most satisfying things I’ve
